CSS

/* Token semantic references the primitive token → easy to change theme */
:root {
  --blue-500: #3b82f6;        /* primitive */
  --color-primary: var(--blue-500); /* semantic */
}
[data-theme="dark"] {
  --color-primary: var(--blue-300);
}
/* Component only uses semantic token, does not hardcode color */
.btn { background: var(--color-primary); }

Versioning & breaking changes
    A component library should use semantic versioning. Changing a required prop = major version. Provide a codemod to automatically migrate, and deprecation warning at least 1 version before removal. This maintains trust with teams using it.

Trade-off worth discussing
    "Flexible" component (many props) vs "opinionated" component (few choices, high consistency). A good library often uses compound components and slots to be both flexible and consistent, rather than stuffing 30 boolean props.

QUIZ 16
    Why should "semantic token" (--color-primary) be separated from "primitive token" (--blue-500)?

      ATo make the CSS file smaller
      BTo change the theme/brand by simply referencing the semantic token, without modifying each component
      CVecause the browser requires it
      DTo avoid using CSS variables

    Explanation: Components only reference semantic tokens. When changing the theme (day/night, changing brand), you only reference the semantic token to a different primitive, and all components update accordingly. Answer B.

